# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1997-world-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Location of Santa Clara, the host city, in California on the west coast of the United States.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The **1981 World Games** were the first World Games, an international multi-sport event, and were held in Santa Clara, California, United States.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Best estimates for attendance figures were that about 80,000 spectators witnessed the first World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The World Games Council was formed independently of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and adopted policies designed to avoid problems that had plagued the Olympic Games for several decades.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] For example, construction of new facilities was not required or encouraged.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Any flags displayed at ceremonies and Games sites were limited to the flags of the participating sports federations.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] No national anthems were played nor national flags displayed.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Athletes entered the opening ceremonies grouped by sport under individual federation banners rather than by country.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Athletes also were housed according to sport.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The respective sport federations paid for each athlete's housing, food and airfare.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The decision to stage World Games I was finalized in January, 1981.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The organizing efforts were seriously set back when the Games' promotions agency, Global Sports Management of New York, pulled out in the final months.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] "It's a humble beginning to what we think is going to be a hard-earned, but successful and regularly-held international event.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] It's a miracle it is taking place at all," said World Games I promotions and sales coordinator Kent Hertenrath.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Kim Un-yong, president of the World Games executive committee, opened the Games with a brief address. “Our theme is sport for the sake of sport and a total disregard for where an athlete comes from,” said Kim.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Casey Conrad, executive director of the President’s Council on Physical Fitness, represented U.S.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] President Ronald Reagan, who had survived an assassination attempt four months earlier, in greeting the athletes.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Governor of California Jerry Brown had planned to attend the opening ceremonies.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] But that summer, when Mediterranean fruit flies were discovered in the Santa Clara Valley, Brown withdrew to focus on emergency eradication efforts.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The Soviet Union had been invited to send athletes but, in the aftermath of the boycotted 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow, instead worked to prevent the competition from ever occurring.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] An event-day official of the casting governing body said that it had located the casting venue on land, which was preferred by the Eastern Bloc nations, instead of on water, as was the usual practice, in a failed effort to encourage their participation (personal communication, August 1, 1981).
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Games secretary-general Don Porter said that some of the problems encountered in the first World Games were created by the International Olympic Committee, especially the Eastern Bloc countries.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Porter said that the national Olympic committees of these countries, as well as the IOC, had intensely pressured the World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] He stated, “I think the International Olympic Committee is very concerned about World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] We’re not competing with the Olympic Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] In fact, the World Games were organized to welcome both Olympic and non-Olympic sports.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The sport governing bodies that were members of the World Games Council desired to be accepted eventually into the Olympic Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Looking to the future, the Council sought to rule out the potential for the IOC to deny a sport’s Olympic acceptance based on an exclusion of the Olympic sports from the World Games program.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Therefore, the World Games Council encouraged the participation of the sport federations of the Olympic Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Indeed, the Olympic sport of boxing was to have been contested in these games and was featured on organizers' promotional materials.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] However, AIBA withdrew the sport from the program in the weeks before the opening of the games because of IOC disapproval.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Don Porter stated that, according to the president of AIBA, Don Hall, the IOC threatened to exclude boxing from the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics if AIBA participated in the World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] In the morning after the close of these Games, U.S. air traffic controllers went on a nationwide strike, leaving some athletes temporarily stranded.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] As for the competition, Games officials expressed great satisfaction.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Kim said, "The important thing was the competition, and in that regard, the Games were a big success." Kim presented the city of Santa Clara with the first official Games flag.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The executive director of World Games I, John Bragg, envisioned more than 50 sports participating in future events.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] "[H]opefully we will set the trend for many World Games to come. ... ," he said.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] "People here are beginning to realize that this is not just another competition.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] 58 nations sent athletes to the first World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The People’s Republic of China was the only communist country represented.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] (Poland was expected but evidently did not show.) Mainland China had not participated in a summer international multi-sport competition since one athlete competed in the 1952 Summer Olympics.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] China participated only in badminton, capturing four of the five gold medals.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] World records in waterskiing and powerlifting highlighted the first weekend of competition.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Ana Maria Carrasco of Venezuela broke her own world record in waterskiing tricks.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] In the 100 kg class in powerlifting, Jim Cash of the U.S. set world records in both dead lift and total lift.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Two athletes each won four individual gold medals in these games: Steve Rajeff of the U.S. in casting and Juergen Kolenda of West Germany in finswimming.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] Tom Peterson of the U.S., in roller speed skating, and Anne-Marie Rouchon of France, in finswimming, won three each.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] For seven World Games sports, according to their federation presidents at the time, the strongest competition ever held in those individual events was fielded at these Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] 104 titles were awarded in 16 sports, including one belatedly designated an "invitational" or demonstration sport.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] An invitational sport program did not exist at the time.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] An agreement was reached with FINA in the lead-up to the games not to allow women's water polo athletes to march in the opening ceremony, to assuage the displeasure of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) for its being included in the program.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The medal tally during the first World Games follows.
[src:1997-world-games/1981-world-games] The United States was at the top of the final medal table.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The **1985 World Games** were the second edition of the World Games, an international multi-sport event held in London.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Three main venues were used, the main one being the Crystal Palace National Sports Centre.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The opening ceremony was held at the Wembley Conference Centre.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The master of ceremonies was television commentator Ron Pickering.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Competitors were addressed by World Games Association President Dr Un Yong Kim, who told competitors, "the World Games is an innovation that deserves a warm welcome." Games Patron Ryoichi Sasakawa underwrote the financial shortfall to enable the Games to take place.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] British Olympic Association Chairman Charles Palmer opened the Games on behalf of the British sports community.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The song "World Game" by John Denver was adopted as the theme for the Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Sports included field archery, taekwondo, karate, sambo, powerlifting, finswimming, roller sports, casting, korfball, water skiing, speedway, fistball, softball and netball.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The ground team at Crystal Palace was headed by former Nottingham Forest player Roy Dwight with assistance from Tosh Chamberlain.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Television coverage was produced by Cheerleader productions.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Commentators included Simon Reed, Martin Tyler, Gerald Sinstadt and Dave Lanning.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] 134 titles were awarded in 22 sports (not including two invitational sports).
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Venues included Wembley Conference Centre, Princes Club (Bedfont), Copthall Stadium.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Wimbledon Stadium, Crystal Palace, David Lloyd Club, Tolmers Scout Camp and Stevenage Bowling Center.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] The medal tally during the second World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Italy finished at the top of the medal standings.
[src:1997-world-games/1985-world-games] Two bronze medals were awarded in fistball and in each karate-kumite (9) and taekwondo (8) event.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] The **1989 World Games** (German: *1989 Weltspiele*), commonly known as **Karlsruhe 1989**, were the third edition of the World Games, an international multi-sport event.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] This edition was held in Karlsruhe, West Germany.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] 112 titles were awarded in 19 sports (5 invitational sports not included).
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] Italy won the most gold medals in this edition; West Germany led in overall medals.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] Two bronze medals were awarded in the men's karate kata event and in each karate kumite (10) and taekwondo (12) event.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] It was the only time that Soviet Union participated in the World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/1989-world-games] The opening event was created and organised by the Traumfabrik theater.
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] The **1993 World Games** (Dutch: *1993 Wereldspelen*), the fourth World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in The Hague, Netherlands.
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] 155 titles were awarded in 23 sports (not including invitational sports — aikido, equestrian vaulting, indoor tug of war, baton twirling and barefoot waterski).
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] The medal tally during the fourth World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] Germany finished at the top of the final medal table.
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] There were two gold medals (and zero silver medals) awarded in five of the acrobatic gymnastics events because of ties for first place.
[src:1997-world-games/1993-world-games] There were two bronze medals awarded in the karate kumite (10) and taekwondo (12) events and one of the acrobatic gymnastics events.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] The **1997 World Games** (Finnish: *1997 Maailman Pelit*, Swedish: *1997 Världsspelen*), the fifth World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in Lahti, Finland on August 7–17, 1997.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] The opening and closing ceremonies took place at the Lahti Sport Centre.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] The 1997 World Games programme featured 23 official sports and 5 invitational sports.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] (Aikido was deemed a demonstration sport; no medal events were held.) The numbers in parentheses indicate the number of medal events that were contested in each sports discipline.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] The medal tally during the fifth World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] United States finished at the top of the final medal table.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] Two bronze medals were awarded in each of the nine karate kumite events.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] No bronze medals were awarded in two bodybuilding and three weightlifting events.
[src:1997-world-games/1997-world-games] No silver medal was awarded in one weightlifting event.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] The **2001 World Games** (Japanese: 2001年ワールドゲームズ, romanized: *2001-Nen wārudogēmuzu*), the sixth World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in Akita, Japan.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] 140 titles (invitational sports not included) were awarded in the following official sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] There were five invitational sports in this edition.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] The 2001 World Games programme featured 27 official sports and 4 invitational sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] The results from the 2001 World Games are from the archived website of the Akita, Japan, organizing committee.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] The medal tally during the sixth World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/2001-world-games] Russia finished at the top of the final medal table.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] The **2005 World Games** (German: *Weltspiele 2005*), the seventh World Games, also known as **Duisburg 2005**, were an international multi-sport event held in Duisburg, Germany from 14 July 2005 until 24 July 2005.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] Three other cities, namely Bottrop, Mülheim an der Ruhr, and Oberhausen, also held some of the competition events.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] More than 3,000 athletes competed in 31 official sports and 6 invitational sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] The 2005 World Games programme featured 31 official sports, and 6 invitational sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] The numbers in parentheses indicate the number of medal events, which were contested in each sports discipline.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] Aikido was also one of the invitational sports, but it was deemed a demonstration sport; no medal events were held.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] The medal tally during the seventh World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] Russia won the most gold medals and tied with Germany in overall medals won in this edition's official sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] There was a tie for second place in one sport climbing event (two silver and no bronze medals awarded).
[src:1997-world-games/2005-world-games] Two bronze medals were awarded in each of the two squash events.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The **2009 World Games** (2009年世界運動會), also known as **Kaohsiung 2009**, the eighth edition of the World Games, were an international multi-sport event held in Kaohsiung, Taiwan (under the name Chinese Taipei) from 16 July 2009 to 26 July 2009.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The games featured sports that are not contested in the Olympic Games.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] 2908 athletes and over 4400 volunteers and others from over 100 countries participated in the 2009 Kaohsiung World Games, setting a record high for the multi-sport competition.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The design of the emblem for The World Games 2009 is based on the first Chinese character in the city's name.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The character "gāo" (高) means high or superior in English.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The toponym stylized as a multicolored ribbon aims to create an atmosphere of festivity and celebration.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The warm colors, orange and magenta, at the top and green and blue at the bottom symbolize the sun rising over the ocean and mirror Kaohsiung well: a passionate city with plenty of sunshine – a vibrant metropolis by the sea.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Gao Mei (高妹) and Syong Ge (雄哥) are named after the host city, Kaohsiung (according to Tongyong Pinyin).
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] They are intended to personify it as "a city of the sea and the sun", to emphasize "ecology and environmental protection", and to symbolize the "friendliness and hospitality" of the city's residents.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The opening ceremony, on July 16, was held in the Main Stadium, and involved 4,000 performers.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] It was designed to provide "a platform for the world to understand Taiwan better", and focused on music, dancing and depictions of Taiwanese culture, including its aboriginal culture.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The ceremony was watched by an estimated 100 million people worldwide.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Among the foreign dignitaries in attendance was the President of Nauru, Marcus Stephen, one of Taiwan's diplomatic allies and himself a former athlete, having won seven gold medals in weightlifting at the Commonwealth Games.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Although China had sent athletes to compete, they were absent from the opening ceremony, reportedly due to Ma Ying-jeou inaugurating the Games in his capacity as the head of state.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Kaohsiung Mayor Chen Chu said the city has shown "soft" power in staging The World Games that concluded and praised Kaohsiung residents for their passion in participating in the event.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Chen noted Froehlich's praise of Kaohsiung, which she said has displayed friendship, cooperation and community participation, and offered her best wishes to Cali, Colombia, which will host the next World Games in 2013.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] She said Kaohsiung is an open, rich and pluralistic city that respects human rights and tolerates different views and political stances as long as they are expressed in a peaceful manners.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Concerning the absence of the athletes from China, which was reported to be a boycott, from the opening and closing ceremonies of The World Games, she said that as a big country, she expected it to show more grace and tolerance.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The 2009 World Games programme featured 31 official sports, and 5 invitational sports.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] On 16 September 2009, the IWGA announced that there had been several doping violations at the recently completed 2009 Games.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] On 26 October 2009, the IWGA Anti-Doping Panel decided on punitive measures against five medal-winners (four bodybuilders and a sumo athlete).
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The measures included the stripping of three gold and two silver medals, as well as lifetime bans from The World Games for three bodybuilders.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The IWGA has made no announcement of reallocation of the forfeited bodybuilding medals.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The International Sumo Federation reallocated the medals for the affected sumo event.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] In 2010, all medals in the sport of bodybuilding were removed from the medal table at the host organizer's website (*worldgames2009.tw*, "The World Games 2009 Kaohsiung"), which is now archived.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] However, all medals as first bestowed still appear at The World Games website (*theworldgames.org*) in both look-up and full result reports.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The sport of bodybuilding has not appeared at a subsequent edition of The World Games.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The medal tally during the eighth World Games is as follows.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Excluded are four bodybuilding medals forfeited for doping and not reallocated.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] In two events there were two bronze medals awarded because of ties for third-place: women's 100m finswimming and women's life saving combined relay.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Hungary was stripped of a gold medal in sumo for doping.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] This table reflects the reallocation of medals specified by the International Sumo Federation.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] In the following calendar for The World Games 2009, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] Each bullet in these boxes is an event final, the number of bullets per box representing the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] On the left the calendar lists each sport with events held during the Games, and at the right how many gold medals were won in that sport.
[src:1997-world-games/2009-world-games] There is a key at the top of the calendar to aid the reader.
